text: so how high will it go now? netadvisor published a listing of predictions (as did many other websites) with so-called cryptocurrency experts calling for up to $100k by the end of 2021.  unfortunately cryptocurrencies are not rockets with a constant release of fuel that causes them to go ever-and-ever faster (or in this case higher and higher in value).  they are part of oscillating cycles that go up and down as they have ever since they started operating and if you donโt build oscillations into your forecast then you are just schilling and hyping a category that i think most of these โexpertsโ fall into.   my conservative projection from 01 jan 2021 was for a value for btc/usdt of $48623 by end 31 dec 2021 and if it ends up off by up to 10% either way (a range of $43.7k to $53.4k) i will still call it a hell of a lot better than most of the projections iโve seen published this year.  based on a current value of $49461 and only 26 days to the end of the year i still have a good chance of being correct.

text: who buys btc at $60k when all past indicators have shown the value is likely to drop by as much as 50% after hitting a peak? who buys btc at $63k when the chance of profit is less than 5% unless the coin is going up past a previous high established just a week earlier?   certainly not any trader i know of.  the only answer i see is a corporate entity who has a plan for keeping the value of btc/usdt above $60k.  since 25 oct there have been at least 16 pushes that resulted in btc/usdt staying above $60k and eventually up to a new record of just over $69k.  in summary an unidentified corporate or grouping of corporates has identified how to keep btc/usdt value stable and above $60k protecting their investments and providing a base line for a continued increase in value.  however maintaining a stable coin value requires a constant influx of investment and it is uncertain how long the organizer of this stability can keep up the investment.  it is likely that the investments are coordinated with shorts and longs that take advantage of knowing when the next investment will occur to push the value back up again.  it is unlikely that any group of traders or even whales can counter this corporate interference.  unfortunately i donโt know how they are doing it or how the use of stablecoins makes this possible but it appears to be working at this time.  but i can recognize interference in established patterns and i see interference going on here.  how rich do you need to be to do this?  i am thinking this would require a slush fund of about $10 billion

text: part a3 โ the phantom menace) the third phase is the rise of the cryptocurrency influencer (โcrypto-jediโ?) running from feb 2021 to oct 2021.  with tesla revealing their purchases of $1.5 billion worth of cryptocurrencies (on 02 feb 2021) and elon musk advocating cryptocurrency as a valid investment the negative news articles posted about the dangers of cryptocurrencies disappear; if elon musk supports it it must be great!  (there are many other influencers or events that could be cited as causes for increased popularity but this is my assessment of the most influential).  however the cryptocurrencies remain just as volatile; traders and whales buy and sell based on reactions from the postings of influencers creating self-fulfilling prophesies (and values).  the increased positive reviews of cryptocurrency investments leads to even greater acceptance of cryptocurrencies as a valid investment and a means of purchasing items like vehicles and houses.  however even the influencers are erratic with great swings in value based on whether their comments are negative or positive.  the value of btc/usdt rises on 20 oct 2021 to a new high of just over $66000.

text: part a2 โ a new hope) the second phase ran from october 2020 to jan 2021.  amid reports of increased corporate interest as early as jan 2020 the reports in oct 2020 of square inc buying 4709 bitcoins for a total price of $50 million (averaging $10.6k each) was just the tip of the iceberg.  hundreds of credible corporations in north america europe and asia began covertly investing in cryptocurrencies.  as the value of btc/usdt rose past $34k at the end of jan 2021 the value was still being affected by whale-level buys and sells but caution was setting in.  instead of whales pushing values up it was likely that most of this increase was due to corporate purchases being held for long-term investment.  in turn massive fomo set in as no one wanted to sell their btc/usdt at $34k only to see it rise higher.  in addition the value was extremely erratic and volatile with the value of btc/usdt rising and falling by as much as $10k over a 48 hour period; any large sell-off sent the value crashing dramatically and any large purchase causes a massive skyrocket upwards.  an excellent era for daily traders and โleveragersโ who have made the right call.  of note coordinated groups that i think of as mmot (massive multiplayer online traders) were still able to take on corporate giants (i.e. redditors vs wall street hedge funds).https://squareup.com/us/en/press/2020-bitcoin-investment

๐ implied volatility:.the supply/demand % in which the.contracts are being traded at. higher.implied volatility means more people.are interested in trading those.contracts as there is usually a.catalyst behind it such as news or.earnings. regular implied volatility.sits around 50% and anything above.that means there is higher demand..be careful though trading options.with high implied volatility (over 90%).as they can have an "iv crush" which.is when the volatility goes back to.normal levels.
๐ volume:.this refers to the total contracts.traded in a given trading session..just like with any other stock higher.volume means better price action.and more liquid trades.

๐ open interest:.the total number of option contracts.that are currently out there. meaning.they have been traded but not yet.liquidated. this does not update.throughout the day. but usually the.higher the open interest the better.that contract selection looks to.investors as it shows larger holdings.at a specific price.

now this might get a bit heady and.confusing here. but no worries as.most options traders focus on delta.and theta. however i will still explain.how these all come to fruition.

a. __delta:__ the amount in which the.option premium is expected to move.on a $1 change in the underlying.stock value..b. __theta:__ theta is when contract.decay starts to happen as the time in.the day starts to diminish the.contract will lose premium..c. __gamma:__ the rate that delta will.change based on a $1 change in the.underlying stock price. aka the.speed at which the premium will.move with the delta..d. __vega:__ as the implied volatility.changes this is the amount the.option premium will change up or.down with time..e. __rho:__ this is the amount the.option premium will change based on.a percentage change in interest rate.

to prevent this decay from.happening some people choose.longer expirations to combat this..others will choose daily or weekly.contracts because there is more.volatility which = more price action to.day trade.

time value means that the longer the.contract has until expiration then the.less "time decay" it has. less time.decay means less volatility in.swinging a specific contract. since.everyday contracts will lose value in."time decay. the closer you get to.expiration the faster the time decay.takes over as seen on the chart.
a time value chart will be provided for.a visual example. when time is.involved this is where another greek.gets involved called theta.
since you have more time for the.underlying stock to move up or down.you will pay a higher premium as less.risk is associated with this type of.play.
no matter what expiration you.choose one thing can be certain the.further out you go in expiration the.more expensive the contract will be.

as discussed above different strikes.have different prices. the same.concept is applied for expirations..optionable stocks will have.expiration attached to the contract.that you can purchase. as mentioned.some will have weeklies all the way.to yearlys and others might just have.monthlies or biweeklies.
no matter what expiration selection.is important for any investor as you.must pick one to trade an option..however different expirations have.different prices attached to the strike.price.

for some the expiration is the most.important part as it gives solidified.dates for swing and longer-term.trades. whereas others buy and sell.in the same day and expiration just.plays into the price of the contract.

text: the curve wars vol.1.in this two-part series we want to outline the whole curve universe and help you gain an understanding what is happening and why it is important...what is curve?.curve is an automated market maker (amm) exchange that is based on an improved model of the bonding curve and focused on trading similarly priced assets like stablecoins or different forms of wrapped btc (for example renbtc and wbtc). this design minimizes impermanent loss slippage and fees. because pools with similar assets are trending towards the same price it is unlikely that any token inside the pool will slide too far of peg. with much smaller fluctuations as opposed to a pool with heterogenic assets the trading fees are much smaller as on other amms (fees are used to compensate liquidity providers for impermanent loss so when we have reduced risk of impermant loss we can offer lower fees). and these smaller fees attract liquidity and the deeper the liquidity the lesser the slippage. a perfect circle:..reduced il -> reduced fees -> increasing liquidity -> smaller fees..on top of that comes an underlying functionality of curve that allows the assets into the pools to automatically get lent out to interest-paying platforms like compound aave and synthetix. this way curve can reward lps not only with trading fees and instead offer interest rates on top of that...the backbone of
